## Refactoring Analysis

### Naming Evaluation (FIRST PRIORITY)

Looking at recent context: the test "claim references item not in policy → CLI errors" passes because `validateDamagesAgainstPolicy` uses `remainingSlots` to also handle items not in the policy. The function's name and error message focus on "more damages than the policy covers" — but it now also handles the case where the policy doesn't cover that itemType at all.

Looking at `validateDamagesAgainstPolicy`:
- The error message says "claim references more 'X' damages than the policy covers"
- But it triggers for both cases: (a) item not in policy at all, (b) too many damages of a covered type

Both messages technically remain correct ("more than 0 covers = 0"), but the function now serves dual purpose. The name `validateDamagesAgainstPolicy` actually captures both cases well, since "validate damages against policy" includes "the damaged itemType must be on policy AND count must not exceed slots."

Also notice `policyItemOfType` has a comment saying "CLI rejects claims for items not on the policy upstream" — this comment is now stale because `validateDamagesAgainstPolicy` itself does that rejection in the same `settleClaimAgainstPolicyCap` call. Let me update.

### APP Mass — Current `validateDamagesAgainstPolicy`

```typescript
const validateDamagesAgainstPolicy = (damages, policyItems): void => {
  const remainingSlots = countOccurrences(policyItems, (item) => item.type);
  for (const damage of damages) {
    const slotsLeft = remainingSlots.get(damage.itemType) ?? 0;
    if (slotsLeft === 0) {
      throw new Error(
        `claim references more '${damage.itemType}' damages than the policy covers`,
      );
    }
    remainingSlots.set(damage.itemType, slotsLeft - 1);
  }
};
```

